<h2>What Is a Put Option? (The Simplest Explanation)</h2>

<p>A <strong>put option</strong> is a bet that a stock's price will go <strong>down</strong>.</p>

<p>Think of it like buying insurance against a stock. When you buy a put, you're buying the <em>right</em> to sell 100 shares of a stock at a specific price (the "strike price") by a specific date. You don't need to own the shares — you just need the stock to drop.</p>

<div class="callout info">
  <div class="callout-title">Analogy — The Concert Ticket</div>
  <p>Imagine you think a concert is going to get cancelled. You buy a "refund guarantee" for $20 that lets you sell a $120 ticket at face value no matter what. If the concert gets cancelled and tickets become worthless, your $20 guarantee is now worth $120. If the concert happens and tickets stay at $120, your guarantee expires worthless — you just lose the $20 you paid.</p>
</div>

<p>That's exactly what a put option is. I paid <strong>$635</strong> for the right to "sell" PLTR at <strong>$120/share</strong>. If PLTR drops significantly below $120, that right becomes very valuable. If PLTR stays above $120, my $635 goes to zero.</p>

